 which norms governing citizenship can legitimately vary. This argument is challenged and developed in responses by Joseph Carens, David Miller, Iseult Honohan, Will Kymlicka and Sue Donaldson, David Owen and Peter J. Spiro. In the concluding chapter, Bauböck replies to his critics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aPolitical Studies 2019. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aaffected interests.  aall affected interests.  aall citizenship stakeholders.  aall subject to coercion.  abirthright.  acitizenship.  ademocratic inclusion.  ademocratic theory.  ainclusion.  alocal citizenship.  alocal polities.  amembership.  amultilevel democracy.  anaturalisation.  apolitical community.  aregional polities.  aself-government.  astakeholder inclusion.  astakeholder principle.  astate polities.1 aBauböck, Rainer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarens, Joseph H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDonaldson, Sue, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHonohan, Iseult, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKymlicka, Will, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOwen, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpiro, Peter J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2017 eBook-Packagez978311128281740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526105257zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/978152